<h2>FAQ</h2>
<p><strong>Do transition words directly improve SEO rankings?</strong></p>
<p>Transition words do not directly affect rankings. They improve readability and time on page, which are indirect ranking signals. They also help Google understand text structure for featured snippets.</p>
<p><strong>How many transition words should I use per paragraph?</strong></p>
<p>Aim for 1-2 transition words per paragraph of 3-5 sentences. The goal is natural flow, not mechanical insertion.</p>
<p><strong>What are the most important transition words for SEO?</strong></p>
<p>Sequence words (first, next, finally) help how-to content earn featured snippets. Cause-and-effect words (therefore, as a result) strengthen explanatory content. Contrast words (however, on the other hand) improve comparison content.</p>
<p><strong>Can I use transition words in headings?</strong></p>
<p>Yes, but sparingly. Headings should be scannable. A heading like "However, SEO Takes Time" is weaker than "Why SEO Takes Time." Save transitions for body text.</p>
<p><strong>Do transition words help with featured snippets?</strong></p>
<p>Yes. List and how-to featured snippets favor content with clear sequence transitions. Paragraph snippets favor content with direct answers followed by explanatory transitions.</p>
<p><strong>What is the best way to practice using transition words?</strong></p>
<p>Read your content aloud. When you stumble or feel a jump between ideas, insert a transition. Over time, this becomes automatic.</p>
